/*****************************************************************************
    bytecode — incant-side bytecode dispatch (interpret).

    interpret(body) walks a bytecoded action body and runs each op.

    Dispatch (post bcOPs->Operators fold, 2026-05-30):
        an instruction's tag resolves against the Operators registry; that
        entry's `interpret` sub-attribute is the C++ handler.
            op      = Operators[grup.taG];
            handler = op.interpret;
            result  = handler(grup);
        One registry, one lookup -- no bcOPs, no fallback. (Works because the
        bcBR/bcBRZ/bcPushLit/... entries were folded into Operators carrying
        interpret= but no operateMethod.)

    Stack-form (2026-05-30): operands live on an operand stack hung off the
    body as its `opStack` attribute -- a plain field used as a stack via
    push/pop. interpret() creates it here; producers (bcPushLit/bcPushField)
    push, consumers/op-shims (bcStoreField/runGT/runMultiply) pop, and the
    branch label rides on the instruction's `dst` attribute. Handlers reach the
    stack via opStackOf(instr) -> instr.parent.getAttribute("opStack").

    Successor convention (unchanged):
        result == null  -> fall through to the next sibling instruction.
        result != null  -> branch; reassign grup so the walk continues from the
                           returned target.

    MACHINERY NOTE (unresolved, incant-side -- flag for Tony/Clay): this is a
    MEMBER walk (`for grup in body; members`). For it to see the instructions,
    emitBC must attach them as MEMBERS of bcLIST. emitBC today uses `+%`
    (opAddAttribute = attributes), so as written this loop would iterate
    nothing. Reconcile the emit side: instructions as members, opStack left as
    an attribute (so the member walk skips it while opStackOf still finds it via
    getAttribute). This is the long-flagged members-vs-attributes discrepancy.
*****************************************************************************/
register(Bytecoding);
define
    interpret body; {
        body +% opStack;
        for grup in body; members
            handler = grup.interpret;
            if !handler;
                print "interpret: no handler for" grup.taG:;
                return;
            result = handler(grup);
            if result;  grup = result;
        if opStack.listLengtH;  print "interpret: opStack not empty at end:" opStack.listLengtH:;
        }
    ;
